										<h1>Developments</h1>
				<p>News items relevant to the policy dialogue on S&amp;T for Development.</p>
						<br class="cl"/>
		</div> 
		<div id="listing-items">
			
							
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/World-Bank-Uganda-set-up-agricultural-grant" title="World Bank, Uganda set up agricultural grant " alt="link">World Bank, Uganda set up agricultural grant </a></h2>

	
					<p> Under-funding has often stood in the way of agricultural research institutions in Africa. A new grant, worked between Uganda and World Bank hopes to revamp farming in the country that was once called the ‘pearl of Africa’. The World Bank has partnered with the Uganda government to offer a grant of USD840,000 to agricultural research institutions in the country. According to Dr. Emily Twinamasiko, director of the National Agricultural Research Organisation (NARO), both public and private research institutions would benefit from the competitive grant. $300,000 of the grant would cater for agricultural zoning. Under this category, there are six grants, each worth $50,000 per project for three years. At the national level, there are six grants, which will benefit six institutions, each worth $90,000. All applicants, she said, would be evaluated on their technical capacity, experience, managerial and control systems required to implement the projects. According to studies, the low productivity observed in Ugandan agriculture is not only a consequence of a lack of relevant agricultural technologies, but also of an adequate interface between research, extension and farmers themselves. During the 20-year war in Uganda's north, the Lord's Resistance Army used bushes for cover, and left many stripped of farming tools, displaced, and surviving only by planting small crops for subsistence. (Source: Africa Science News Service, 24 December 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/World-Bank-Uganda-set-up-agricultural-grant">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Brussels-sees-scramble-to-do-science-with-Africa" title="Brussels sees scramble to do science with Africa " alt="link">Brussels sees scramble to do science with Africa </a></h2>

	
					<p> A new initiative to boost cooperation sparks duplication concerns. As Europe and Africa prepare to work more closely on science and technology, an initiative to boost research collaboration between the two continents has been coolly received by EU bureaucrats who fear it may hamper their own science linkages. Science with Africa, a non-profit initiative based in Brussels, is staging a conference for scientists and policymakers in Addis Ababa in March next year. Using funding from public and private sources, it also hopes to boost international science collaboration with Africa through an office in the Ethiopian capital. The initiative follows hot on the heels of the Africa-EU strategy, which was adopted by heads of state on 9 December. The strategy lays the groundwork for the EU to build science capacity in Africa and is seen by many as an attempt by Europe to re-establish itself as the trade partner of choice for Africa, which is being wooed by emerging economies like China and India. The popularity of Science with Africa worries EU officials, who are also planning to set up a permanent office in the Ethiopian capital. They are afraid that Science with Africa will become an unnecessary go-between for Africans trying to access European science funding. Speaking at the parliamentary hearing, Rudolf Meijer of the European Commission’s research division said that while the initiative was ‘welcome as a private initiative, potentially useful for awareness raising, dissemination of information and match-making for cooperation and technology transfer’, it should not substitute EU representation in Africa. (Source: Research Africa, 18 December 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Brussels-sees-scramble-to-do-science-with-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/ADB-funds-200m-skills-programme" title="ADB funds $200m skills programme " alt="link">ADB funds $200m skills programme </a></h2>

	
					<p> The African Development Bank (ADB) is preparing to disburse $192.4 million to build skills on the continent. The funds are likely to be released to six countries and two regional bodies next year. ‘The aim is to build science and technology skills for the competitiveness of African economies,’ an ADB official said. Rwanda, Kenya, Mozambique and the two regional bodies will receive their shares of the money in the shape of grants. The Seychelles, Malawi and Equatorial Guinea will receive theirs as loans, since the ADB considers them economically better off. Rwanda will receive a $13 million grant to conduct a study of ways to link industry with the research community to increase productivity. It is also in line for a grant to upgrade equipment at the Kigali Institute of Science and Technology (Kist). (Source: Research Africa, 18 December 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/ADB-funds-200m-skills-programme">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Multinational-corporations-gaining-total-control-over-farming" title="‘Multinational corporations gaining total control over farming’ " alt="link">‘Multinational corporations gaining total control over farming’ </a></h2>

	
					<p> Food security activists who gathered recently in Penang, Malaysia, said they are now more concerned than ever that farmers are becoming dependent on large multinational corporations for seeds, fertilizers, pesticides, and other inputs while also becoming ‘more vulnerable to pressures’ to grow genetically modified (GM) crops. The activists were gathered for the 25th anniversary of the Pesticide Action Network (PAN): a network of NGOs, institutions, and individuals in over 90 countries. Participants said that agrichemical sales have become increasingly concentrated in a handful of companies, with Syngenta, Bayer, Monsanto, BASF, Dow, and DuPont together controlling 85% of the world pesticide market. Three companies – Cargill, Archer Daniels, and Bunge – control nearly 90% of the global grain trade while 11 firms account for about half of world seed sales, of which about a quarter are sales of GM seeds. Activists were especially concerned about agricultural companies having become more ‘vertically integrated’ – defined as the ‘taking over’ of the entire food production cycle, from the development of proprietary strains of DNA and seed sales down to the distribution and retail sale of food products in supermarkets and ‘hypermarkets.’ (Source: Inter Press Service, 6 December 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Multinational-corporations-gaining-total-control-over-farming">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Biofuel-holds-promise-for-Caribbean" title="Biofuel holds promise for Caribbean " alt="link">Biofuel holds promise for Caribbean </a></h2>

	
					<p> Small Caribbean nations see big biofuel opportunities in ethanol produced from traditional sugar crops and biodiesel from promising African palm and jatropha trees, delegates to a conference in Miami said. While the push for alternative fuels will probably not revive the failing centuries-old Caribbean sugar industry, countries like El Salvador have room to increase production, delegates said. Regional governments, however, need immediately to pass legislation mandating that gasoline be blended with ethanol so that farmers can feel confident that biofuels are the future, said Julio Arroyo of the Sugar Association of El Salvador. ‘We have 60,000 hectares (148,300 acres) of sugar. We have 300,000 hectares (741,300 acres) that are not being used, so there is a lot of opportunity,’ he said. ‘But without legislation, this industry is not going to develop.’ The Bush administration's push to increase U.S. use and production of alternative fuels as a way to lessen dependence on foreign oil spurred interest in the Caribbean basin, where shaky economies have struggled to cope with globalization. (Source: Reuters, 5 December 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Biofuel-holds-promise-for-Caribbean">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/PNG-palm-oil-firm-eyes-expansion" title="PNG palm oil firm eyes expansion " alt="link">PNG palm oil firm eyes expansion </a></h2>

	
					<p> Papua New Guinea's largest palm oil producer, New Britain Palm Oil, said on Wednesday it plans to list in London and raise £88.9 million (US$182 million). The firm hopes to benefit from a near doubling in the price of palm oil in the last year, driven by demand for biofuels and economic growth in China and India. Palm oil is also used for cooking and in products such as soap and ice cream. The company, which has 40,000 hectares of palm oil plantations and a refinery, will use the proceeds to accelerate its planting and build infrastructure. Palm-oil based biofuels have caused controversy as critics say they have encouraged the destruction of large parts of rain forest to create new agricultural land, potentially also releasing carbon dioxide from the peat contained in the soil. NBPOL said it is focused on sustainable plantations. (Source: Reuters, 12 December 2008.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/PNG-palm-oil-firm-eyes-expansion">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Paying-farmers-to-protect-the-environment" title="Paying farmers to protect the environment?" alt="link">Paying farmers to protect the environment?</a></h2>

	
					<p> <a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/010/a1200e/a1200e00.htm" target="_blank">State of Food and Agriculture 2007</a>, the FAO argues that carefully targeted payments to farmers could help protect the environment and address climate change, biodiversity loss, and water supply concerns. Agriculture uses more land and water than any other human activity. Current incentives for farmers tend to favor the production of food, fiber, and increasingly, biofuels. However, incentives typically ‘under-value’ other beneficial services that farmers can provide, such as carbon storage, flood control, clean water provision, and biodiversity conservation. The report states that payments for environmental services are one way of increasing incentives to adopt improved agricultural practices and even to offset pollution generated in other sectors. The report notes that hundreds of payment programs for environmental services are currently being implemented around the world, mainly as part of forest conservation initiatives, ‘but relatively few programmes for environmental services have targeted farmers and agricultural lands in developing countries.’ (Source: FAO Newsroom, 15 November 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Paying-farmers-to-protect-the-environment">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-10th-annual-L-Oreal-UNESCO-Awards-for-Women-in-Science" title="The 10th annual L’Oréal–UNESCO Awards for Women in Science " alt="link">The 10th annual L’Oréal–UNESCO Awards for Women in Science </a></h2>

	
					<p> Five distinguished women researchers in the life sciences were named on October 5th 2007 as recipients of the 10th annual L’Oréal-UNESCO Awards for Women in Science. The awards are conferred in life sciences and material sciences in alternating years. With the 2008 Awards in life sciences, a total of 52 women from 26 countries, whose exemplary careers in science have opened up new and sometimes revolutionary ways of improving human well-being, will have been recognized. Through their work, the L’Oréal -UNESCO Awards Laureates are actively tackling the major challenges facing modern science. Award Laureates have made notable advances in such widely diverse fields as ecology and sustainable development; gene therapy and inherited diseases; materials and medicines of the future; and innovative technologies. The Awards will be presented at a ceremony at UNESCO headquarters in Paris on 6 March 2008. Each Laureate receives US$100,000. (Source: UNESCO newsroom, 21 November 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/The-10th-annual-L-Oreal-UNESCO-Awards-for-Women-in-Science">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Ambitious-plan-to-promote-science-technology-literacy-among-SA-youth" title="Ambitious plan to promote science, technology literacy among SA youth " alt="link">Ambitious plan to promote science, technology literacy among SA youth </a></h2>

	
					<p> The DST has launched the Youth into Science Strategy (YiSS) aimed at promoting science and technology literacy among youth in the country. The DST developed the YiSS as part of its goal to promote youth empowerment in science, technology, engineering and mathematics. Ultimately, this is expected to close the skills gap by supporting all efforts to improve the development of high-level researchers, scientists and technologists in the country. The departments of science and technology and education will collaborate in the implementation of the strategy. While it focuses mainly on school-going youth and undergraduate students in the science field other youth interventions are aimed at developing the skills through technical colleges and out of school programmes. Set targets include doubling the number of youth who participate in the National Science Week activities; identifying and nurturing at least 5000 talented youth from disadvantaged background through the DST’s maths and science camps by 2010. (Source: Department Science and Technology (DST) press release, September 2007.)</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Ambitious-plan-to-promote-science-technology-literacy-among-SA-youth">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
