						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Ethiopia-L-Oreal-Woman-Science-Fellow" title="Ethiopia: L’Oreal Woman Science Fellow" alt="link">Ethiopia: L’Oreal Woman Science Fellow</a></h2>

	
					<p> 
Ethiopian scientist Mestawet Taye Asfaw combines a moving and evocative account of the human suffering caused by hunger with a lucid and informative discussion of the ill-advised agricultural practices that transformed her country into a worldwide symbol for famine. ‘Ethiopia has become a symbol for hunger throughout the world. As an Ethiopian studying abroad I am more aware of this than ever. Let me begin by telling what happened to me here in Norway where I am currently living. I was waiting in line at a bank. A very old man with a cane was also waiting, and he asked me where I was from. I told him I was from Ethiopia. He said something to the people around us in Norwegian, and suddenly everyone was looking at me with amazement. I did not understand what was being said and why I had become the center of attention. He turned to me again and said, &quot;But, you do not have food in Ethiopia, right? I felt something burning inside me. I started by saying, &quot;No, it's not like that,&quot; but I could not continue and suddenly my eyes filled with tears. Source: Mestawet Taye Asfaw, UNESCO-l'Oreal For Women in Science Fellow 2007, L’Oreal report, September 2007. </p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Ethiopia-L-Oreal-Woman-Science-Fellow">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/South-Africa-lukewarm-about-jatropha" title="South Africa lukewarm about jatropha" alt="link">South Africa lukewarm about jatropha</a></h2>

	
					<p> Jatropha is seen by some as the answer to the world’s fuel crisis. But it still hugely controversial in South Africa, and the government is not at all sure that the plant will solve the country’s biofuel woes. In the past couple of years biofuels, made out of food commodities such as maize and sugar cane, have been pushing up food prices, raising questions about the effects of biofuel production on food security, especially regarding the poor. But jatropha, a poisonous oilseed that yields an inedible vegetable oil used to make biofuel, does not threaten food security because it is not a food crop. The agriculture department, however, is sceptical about allowing the plant to flourish in the country. South African climatic and environmental constraints and limited agricultural production potential, jatropha is not at the moment considered a viable option as a source for biofuels. Source: Mail and Guardian, 26 September 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/South-Africa-lukewarm-about-jatropha">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Cornell-degree-offered-in-Africa" title="Cornell degree offered in Africa" alt="link">Cornell degree offered in Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p> Cornell University is launching a Cornell master of professional studies degree program in international agriculture and rural development in Ethiopia, through a partnership with Ethiopia's Bahir Dar University. Cornell faculty members will travel to Ethiopia for three weeks at a time to teach intensive courses in topics including hydrology, soils, economics, and program management while collaborating with Bahir Dar faculty. The ultimate goal is to transfer control of what will begin as a Cornell degree program to the six-year-old Ethiopian institution. Cornell University will provide a part of the tuition for students in the program, with the World Bank providing the rest. Source: Inside Higher Ed, 21 September 2001.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Cornell-degree-offered-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Latest-World-Bank-biosafety-proposal-for-West-Africa-heavily-criticised" title="Latest World Bank biosafety proposal for West Africa heavily criticised" alt="link">Latest World Bank biosafety proposal for West Africa heavily criticised</a></h2>

	
					<p> The World Bank has revised and resubmitted its new version of the West African biosafety project to the United Nation's Global Environment Facility after deep concerns were raised by civil society groups and governments with the initial proposal. In response, the Coalition for the Protection of African Genetic Heritage (COPAGEN), which is based across West Africa in Burkina Faso, Benin, Côte d'Ivoire, Guinea Bissau, Guinea Conakry, Mali, Niger, Senegal, and Togo, has reacted angrily to this proposal. The proposal appears to have little support from the grassroots and has blatantly made it difficult for most to participate; participation has been selective and the main language has been English, despite nearly all countries involved having French as their official language. The new proposal is also only available as an enormous file, making it difficult for many people in West Africa to access. Source: GRAIN, September 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Latest-World-Bank-biosafety-proposal-for-West-Africa-heavily-criticised">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/GFAR-to-emphasise-innovation-systems-approach" title="GFAR to emphasise innovation systems approach" alt="link">GFAR to emphasise innovation systems approach</a></h2>

	
					<p> The Global Forum for Agricultural Research (GFAR) has announced that an innovation systems approach – focused on poor, smallholder producers – will guide its strategy and future actions. Representatives of stakeholders from GFAR, a multi-stakeholder initiative that contributes to eradicating poverty, achieving food security, and conserving and managing natural resources, announced at its annual retreat in Alexandria, Cairo, in April that they would emphasise an innovations systems approach that involves partnerships of multiple actors in the public, private and community sector to collaborate toward agricultural development.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/GFAR-to-emphasise-innovation-systems-approach">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Trade-ministers-moot-scheme-to-harness-technology-in-Africa" title="Trade ministers moot scheme to harness technology in Africa" alt="link">Trade ministers moot scheme to harness technology in Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p> Africa is seeking to boost the growth of its industry through a €250 million (US$350m) initiative using technology to bolster production. The scheme, named the African Technology and Innovation Initiative (ATII), has already been adopted by the continental conference of ministers of industry and should take off once heads of state give their approval at a summit next January. The €250 million is just a budget estimate. The funds have not been raised yet, although the AU said it hopes to do so via contributions from member states and international donors. The ATII would set up five African networks harnessing science and technology to shore up the continent’ s industrial base. They will be: the African Network of Design Centres, the African Network of Testing and Certification Centres, the African Network of Technology Transfer and Innovation Centres, the African Network of Business Support Service Centres and the African Network of Environmental Compliance Centre. ‘The activities of these networks – most importantly, technology transfer and innovation – will help in meeting the great technological demand of the African region and hence enable the region to acquire the status of being a technology adopter,’ said the AU in a concept note presented to the conference of ministers of industry at their first extra ordinary session held in Midrand, South Africa from 24 to 27 September. Source: Research Africa, 5 October 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Trade-ministers-moot-scheme-to-harness-technology-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/In-Africa-prosperity-from-seeds-falls-short" title="In Africa, prosperity from seeds falls short" alt="link">In Africa, prosperity from seeds falls short</a></h2>

	
					<p> Even the most promising new crop varieties will not by themselves bring the plentiful harvests to sub-Saharan Africa that can end poverty, because new ways to get the seeds to farmers are needed, as well as broader investment in ‘basics,’ such as roads, credit, and farmer education. Both the private and the agricultural sectors in the region are ‘woefully undeveloped,’ according to the article. Conventionally-bred New Rice for Africa, or Nerica, was developed with financing from wealthy countries and private foundations, and the seeds are ‘a marvel,’ producing bountiful rice crops resistant to drought, pests, and disease. Yet a decade after their introduction, they have spread to only ‘a tiny fraction’ of the land in West Africa where the rice could help millions of farming families escape poverty. ‘This is a story repeated thousands of times all over Africa,’ says Joseph Devries, who is the head of seed development for the Alliance for a Green Revolution in Africa (AGRA). ‘You have farmers who are very willing adopters of new technologies and want to raise yields, but are not getting access to seed, fertilizer and small-scale irrigation.’ He says that finding a sustainable way to supply these farmers with seed ‘is emerging as the holy grail for agricultural development.’ The African Development Bank is financing a US$34 million program in seven countries to promote wider use of the Nerica seeds, but the obstacles are ‘daunting.’ Source: Celia W. Dugger, New York Times, 10 October 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/In-Africa-prosperity-from-seeds-falls-short">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/UN-expert-calls-for-biofuel-moratorium" title="UN expert calls for biofuel moratorium" alt="link">UN expert calls for biofuel moratorium</a></h2>

	
					<p> A UN expert on the right to food has called for a five-year moratorium on the production of biofuel out of concern that it was contributing to hunger by using up increasing amounts of farmland. On the eve of World Food Day, Jean Ziegler countered President Bush's call for an increase in biofuel, arguing farm production should be used to contain hunger instead. ‘You don't have the right, even if you're battling climate change, to (perpetuate) this total massacre’ caused by lack of food, he said. Using biofuels instead of gasoline in cars is generally considered to cut CO2 emissions, although some scientists say greenhouse gases released during the production of biofuel crops can offset those gains. The use of crops for biofuel has become especially predominant in Brazil and the United States. In March 2007, President Bush and President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva of Brazil signed an agreement committing their countries to increased ethanol production. Source: Associated Press, 15 October 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/UN-expert-calls-for-biofuel-moratorium">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Ethiopian-researcher-investigates-dwarf-varieties-of-tef" title="Ethiopian researcher investigates dwarf varieties of tef" alt="link">Ethiopian researcher investigates dwarf varieties of tef</a></h2>

	
					<p> Tef (Eragrostis tef) is Ethiopia's main cereal crop, covering more than one million hectares of land. Its advantages are numerous, such as its capacity to tolerate both drought and waterlogging. However, tef's yields leave much to be desired. The plants are often victims of lodging, a weakness of the stem that causes the plant to fall, over resulting in considerable harvest losses, both in terms of quality and quantity. The FAO estimates the losses to be about 17%. Zerihun Tadele, an Ethiopian researcher at the University of Bern, Switzerland, has been conducting research which he hopes will lead to the development of dwarf tef varieties that will be resistant to lodging, especially after fertiliser applications. With support from the Syngenta Foundation for Sustainable Agriculture, Tadele is using a genetic technique called tilling to identify the genes responsible for the trait that one wishes to modify, which in this case is plant height. The technique has been successfully used on maize, wheat and barley. Tadele has already managed to produce candidate dwarf lines. The final results concerning dwarf tef's performance are expected in June 2008. Source: Oromia Times, 16 October 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Ethiopian-researcher-investigates-dwarf-varieties-of-tef">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Pacific-Improved-access-to-digitised-information-in-fisheries-in-the-Pacific" title="Pacific: Improved access to digitised information in fisheries in the Pacific" alt="link">Pacific: Improved access to digitised information in fisheries in the Pacific</a></h2>

	
					<p> The SPC Library and Marine Resources Division have developed a full text digital library which is now available online. The library offers access to electronic versions (in PDF format) of more than 4300 fisheries and aquaculture-related documents, in French and in English, produced by, for, or in collaboration with SPC. Source: Secretariat of the Pacific Community (SPC), 16 October 2007.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Pacific-Improved-access-to-digitised-information-in-fisheries-in-the-Pacific">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl" />
<p>

